  "response": "**The literal responsible**\n\n`\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` at `src/date.ts:29` — flagged by `crime_00010` (Timezone Roulette).\n\n**Why it fails only in production**\n\nPer the ECMAScript date-parsing rules, the two unsafe literals on lines 29 and 33 behave differently:\n\n- `\"2026-12-20\"` (line 33) — date-only ISO form, spec-mandated to parse as **UTC**. Same in CI and prod.\n- `\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` (line 29) — date-*time* form with no offset, spec-mandated to parse as **local time**.\n\nIn CI (UTC host) the line-29 literal resolves to `2026-12-25T07:00:00Z`. On a European host (UTC+1 in winter) it resolves to `2026-12-25T06:00:00Z` — one hour earlier in absolute time. Any \"is now ≥ promoStart?\" comparison flips an hour sooner, and on the boundary day that reads as \"a day early.\"\n\n**Smallest change**\n\nAppend `Z` to that one literal:\n\n```ts\n// src/date.ts:29\n- new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")\n+ new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\")\n```\n\nThat makes the production parse match the CI parse byte-for-byte. No function rename, no library swap, no signature change. (Line 33's `\"2026-12-20\"` is already UTC by spec, so it doesn't need touching for this bug — though tightening it to `\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\"` would make the invariant visible to readers.)",
